# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: service-level-objectives
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:service-level-objectives/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:service-level-objectives/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:service-level-objectives/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] A **service-level agreement** (**SLA**) is an agreement, typically a binding contract, between a service provider and a customer that define particular aspects of the service – such as quality of service, availability, responsibilities – as terms of contract.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] SLAs are commonly used in the technology industry, and often contain specific service-level objectives for defined service level indicators, such as mean time between failures, mean time to repair, mean time to recovery, network throughput, jitter, uptime, first-call resolution, and turnaround time.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Unlike traditional contracts, SLAs often require parties involved to meet regularly to create an open forum for communication, apply rewards and penalties for performance, and leave room for periodic revisitation to make changes.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] SLAs may be supported by operational-level agreements, or OLAs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Since the late 1980s SLAs have been used by fixed-line telecom operators.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Larger organizations often maintain many SLAs internally, such that two different units in an organization script an SLA with one unit being the customer and another being the service provider.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] This practice helps to maintain the same quality of service amongst different units in the organization and also across multiple locations of the organization.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] This internal scripting of SLA also helps to compare the quality of service between an in-house department and an external service provider.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] The output received by the customer as a result of the service provided is the main focus of the service level agreement.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] It is not uncommon for an internet backbone service provider (or network service provider) to explicitly state its SLA on its website.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Telecommunications Act of 1996 does not expressly mandate that companies have SLAs, but it does provide a framework for firms to do so in Sections 251 and 252.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Section 252(c)(1) for example ("Duty to Negotiate") requires incumbent local exchange carriers (ILECs) to negotiate in good faith about matters such as resale and access to rights of way.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] New emerging technologies such as 5G bring new complexities to the network operators.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] With more stringent SLAs and customer expectations, problem resolutions must be prioritized based on impacted subscribers.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] For fixed networks subscribers, service modeling appears to be one of the most suitable ways to effectively monitor SLA's and ensure they are met.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] A **web service level agreement** (**WSLA**) is a standard for service level agreement compliance monitoring of web services.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] It allows authors to specify the performance metrics associated with a web service application, desired performance targets, and actions that should be performed when performance is not met.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] WSLA Language Specification, version 1.0 was published by IBM in 2001.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] The underlying benefit of cloud computing is shared resources, which are supported by the underlying nature of a shared infrastructure environment.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Thus, SLAs span across the cloud and are offered by service providers as a service-based agreements rather than a customer-based agreements.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Measuring, monitoring and reporting on cloud performance is based on the end UX or their ability to consume resources.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] The downside of cloud computing relative to SLAs is the difficulty in determining the root cause of service interruptions due to the complex nature of the environment.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] As applications are moved from dedicated hardware into the cloud, they need to achieve the same even more demanding levels of service than classical installations.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] SLAs for cloud services focus on characteristics of the data center and more recently include characteristics of the network (see carrier cloud) to support end-to-end SLAs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Any SLA management strategy considers two well-differentiated phases: negotiating the contract and monitoring its fulfillment in real-time.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Thus, SLA management encompasses the SLA contract definition: the basic schema with the QoS parameters; SLA negotiation; SLA monitoring; SLA violation detection; and SLA enforcement—according to defined policies.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] The main point is to build a new layer upon the grid, cloud, or SOA middleware able to create a negotiation mechanism between the providers and consumers of services.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] An example is the EU–funded Framework 7 research project, SLA@SOI, which is researching aspects of multi-level, multi-provider SLAs within service-oriented infrastructure and cloud computing, while another EU-funded project, VISION Cloud, has provided results concerning content-oriented SLAs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] FP7 IRMOS also investigated aspects of translating application-level SLA terms to resource-based attributes to bridge the gap between client-side expectations and cloud-provider resource-management mechanisms.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] A summary of the results of various research projects in the area of SLAs (ranging from specifications to monitoring, management and enforcement) has been provided by the European Commission.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Outsourcing involves the transfer of responsibility from an organization to a supplier.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] This new arrangement is managed through a contract that may include one or more SLAs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] The contract may involve financial penalties and the right to terminate if any of the SLA metrics are consistently missed.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] The setting, tracking and managing SLAs is an important part of the outsourcing relationship management (ORM) discipline.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-agreement] Specific SLAs are typically negotiated upfront as part of the outsourcing contract and used as one of the primary tools of outsourcing governance.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] A **service-level objective** (**SLO**) is a target value or range of values for a service level that is measured by an SLI.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] An SLO is a key element of a service-level agreement (SLA) between a service provider and a customer.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] SLOs are agreed upon as a means of measuring the performance of the service provider and are outlined as a way of avoiding disputes between the two parties based on misunderstanding.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] There is often confusion in the use of SLAs and SLOs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] The SLA is the entire agreement that specifies what service is to be provided, how it is supported, times, locations, costs, performance, and responsibilities of the parties involved.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] SLOs are specific measurable characteristics of the SLA such as availability, throughput, frequency, response time, or quality.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] These SLOs together are meant to define the expected service between the provider and the customer and vary depending on the service's urgency, resources, and budget.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] SLOs provide a quantitative means to define the level of service a customer can expect from a provider.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] The SLO are formed by setting goals for metrics (commonly called service level indicators, SLIs).
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] As an example, an availability SLO may be defined as the expected measured value of an availability SLI over a prescribed duration (e.g. four weeks).
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] The availability SLI used will vary based on the nature and architecture of the service.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] For example, a simple web service might use the ratio of successful responses served vs the total number of valid requests received.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] While Andrieux et al. define the SLO as "the quality of service aspect of the agreement.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] Syntactically, it is an assertion over the terms of the agreement as well as such qualities as date and time".
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] Keller and Ludwig more concisely define an SLO as "commitment to maintain a particular state of the service in a given period" with respect to the state of the SLA parameters.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] Keller and Ludwig go on to state that while service providers will most often be the lead entity in taking on SLOs there is no firm definition as such and any entity can be responsible for an SLO.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] Optionally an EvaluationEvent maybe assigned to the SLO, an EvaluationEvent is defined as the measure by which the SLO will be checked to see whether it's meeting the expression.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] SLOs should generally be specified in terms of an achievement value or service level, a target measurement, a measurement period, and where and how they are measured.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] As an example, "90% of calls to the helpdesk should be answered in less than 20 seconds measured over a one-month period as reported by the ACD system".
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] Results can be reported as a percent of time that the target answer time was achieved and then compared to the desired service level (90%).
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objective] The SLO term is found in various scientific papers, for instance in the reference architecture of the SLA@SOI project, and it is used in the Open Grid Forum document on WS-Agreement.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] It’s impossible to manage a service correctly, let alone well, without understanding which behaviors really matter for that service and how to measure and evaluate those behaviors.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] To this end, we would like to define and deliver a given *level of service* to our users, whether they use an internal API or a public product.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] We use intuition, experience, and an understanding of what users want to define *service level indicators* (SLIs), *objectives* (SLOs), and *agreements* (SLAs).
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] These measurements describe basic properties of metrics that matter, what values we want those metrics to have, and how we’ll react if we can’t provide the expected service.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Ultimately, choosing appropriate metrics helps to drive the right action if something goes wrong, and also gives an SRE team confidence that a service is healthy.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] This chapter describes the framework we use to wrestle with the problems of metric modeling, metric selection, and metric analysis.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Much of this explanation would be quite abstract without an example, so we’ll use the Shakespeare service outlined in Shakespeare: A Sample Service to illustrate our main points.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Many readers are likely familiar with the concept of an SLA, but the terms *SLI* and *SLO* are also worth careful definition, because in common use, the term *SLA* is overloaded and has taken on a number of meanings depending on context.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] We prefer to separate those meanings for clarity.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] An SLI is a service level *indicator*—a carefully defined quantitative measure of some aspect of the level of service that is provided.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Most services consider *request latency*—how long it takes to return a response to a request—as a key SLI.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Other common SLIs include the *error rate*, often expressed as a fraction of all requests received, and *system throughput*, typically measured in requests per second.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] The measurements are often aggregated: i.e., raw data is collected over a measurement window and then turned into a rate, average, or percentile.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Ideally, the SLI directly measures a service level of interest, but sometimes only a proxy is available because the desired measure may be hard to obtain or interpret.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For example, client-side latency is often the more user-relevant metric, but it might only be possible to measure latency at the server.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Another kind of SLI important to SREs is *availability*, or the fraction of the time that a service is usable.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] It is often defined in terms of the fraction of well-formed requests that succeed, sometimes called *yield*.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For example, availabilities of 99% and 99.999% can be referred to as "2 nines" and "5 nines" availability, respectively, and the current published target for Google Compute Engine availability is “three and a half nines”—99.95% availability.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] An SLO is a *service level objective*: a target value or range of values for a service level that is measured by an SLI.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] A natural structure for SLOs is thus *SLI ≤ target*, or *lower bound ≤ SLI ≤ upper bound*.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For example, we might decide that we will return Shakespeare search results "quickly," adopting an SLO that our average search request latency should be less than 100 milliseconds.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] To begin with, you don’t always get to choose its value!
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For incoming HTTP requests from the outside world to your service, the queries per second (QPS) metric is essentially determined by the desires of your users, and you can’t really set an SLO for that.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] On the other hand, you *can* say that you want the average latency per request to be under 100 milliseconds, and setting such a goal could in turn motivate you to write your frontend with low-latency behaviors of various kinds or to buy certain kinds of low-latency equipment.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] (100 milliseconds is obviously an arbitrary value, but in general lower latency numbers are good.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Again, this is more subtle than it might at first appear, in that those two SLIs—QPS and latency—might be connected behind the scenes: higher QPS often leads to larger latencies, and it’s common for services to have a performance cliff beyond some load threshold.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Choosing and publishing SLOs to users sets expectations about how a service will perform.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] This strategy can reduce unfounded complaints to service owners about, for example, the service being slow.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Without an explicit SLO, users often develop their own beliefs about desired performance, which may be unrelated to the beliefs held by the people designing and operating the service.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Finally, SLAs are service level *agreements*: an explicit or implicit contract with your users that includes consequences of meeting (or missing) the SLOs they contain.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] The consequences are most easily recognized when they are financial—a rebate or a penalty—but they can take other forms.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] SRE doesn’t typically get involved in constructing SLAs, because SLAs are closely tied to business and product decisions.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] SRE does, however, get involved in helping to avoid triggering the consequences of missed SLOs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] They can also help to define the SLIs: there obviously needs to be an objective way to measure the SLOs in the agreement, or disagreements will arise.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Google Search is an example of an important service that doesn’t have an SLA for the public: we want everyone to use Search as fluidly and efficiently as possible, but we haven’t signed a contract with the whole world.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Even so, there are still consequences if Search isn’t available—unavailability results in a hit to our reputation, as well as a drop in advertising revenue.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Many other Google services, such as Google for Work, do have explicit SLAs with their users.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Whether or not a particular service has an SLA, it’s valuable to define SLIs and SLOs and use them to manage the service.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] So much for the theory—now for the experience.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Given that we’ve made the case for *why* choosing appropriate metrics to measure your service is important, how do you go about identifying what metrics are meaningful to your service or system?
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] You shouldn’t use every metric you can track in your monitoring system as an SLI; an understanding of what your users want from the system will inform the judicious selection of a few indicators.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Choosing too many indicators makes it hard to pay the right level of attention to the indicators that matter, while choosing too few may leave significant behaviors of your system unexamined.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] We typically find that a handful of representative indicators are enough to evaluate and reason about a system’s health.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Many indicator metrics are most naturally gathered on the server side, using a monitoring system such as Borgmon (see Practical Alerting from Time-Series Data) or Prometheus, or with periodic log analysis—for instance, HTTP 500 responses as a fraction of all requests.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] However, some systems should be instrumented with *client*-side collection, because not measuring behavior at the client can miss a range of problems that affect users but don’t affect server-side metrics.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For example, concentrating on the response latency of the Shakespeare search backend might miss poor user latency due to problems with the page’s JavaScript: in this case, measuring how long it takes for a page to become usable in the browser is a better proxy for what the user actually experiences.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For simplicity and usability, we often aggregate raw measurements.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Some metrics are seemingly straightforward, like the number of requests *per second* served, but even this apparently straightforward measurement implicitly aggregates data over the measurement window.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Is the measurement obtained once a second, or by averaging requests over a minute?
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] The latter may hide much higher instantaneous request rates in bursts that last for only a few seconds.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Consider a system that serves 200 requests/s in even-numbered seconds, and 0 in the others.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] It has the same average load as one that serves a constant 100 requests/s, but has an *instantaneous* load that is twice as large as the *average* one.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Similarly, averaging request latencies may seem attractive, but obscures an important detail: it’s entirely possible for most of the requests to be fast, but for a long tail of requests to be much, much slower.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Most metrics are better thought of as *distributions* rather than averages.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For example, for a latency SLI, some requests will be serviced quickly, while others will invariably take longer—sometimes much longer.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] A simple average can obscure these tail latencies, as well as changes in them.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Figure 4-1 provides an example: although a typical request is served in about 50 ms, 5% of requests are 20 times slower!
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Monitoring and alerting based only on the average latency would show no change in behavior over the course of the day, when there are in fact significant changes in the tail latency (the topmost line).
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Using percentiles for indicators allows you to consider the shape of the distribution and its differing attributes: a high-order percentile, such as the 99th or 99.9th, shows you a plausible worst-case value, while using the 50th percentile (also known as the median) emphasizes the typical case.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] The higher the variance in response times, the more the typical user experience is affected by long-tail behavior, an effect exacerbated at high load by queuing effects.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] User studies have shown that people typically prefer a slightly slower system to one with high variance in response time, so some SRE teams focus only on high percentile values, on the grounds that if the 99.9th percentile behavior is good, then the typical experience is certainly going to be.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] We recommend that you standardize on common definitions for SLIs so that you don’t have to reason about them from first principles each time.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] To save effort, build a set of reusable SLI templates for each common metric; these also make it simpler for everyone to understand what a specific SLI means.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Start by thinking about (or finding out!) what your users care about, not what you can measure.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Often, what your users care about is difficult or impossible to measure, so you’ll end up approximating users’ needs in some way.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] However, if you simply start with what’s easy to measure, you’ll end up with less useful SLOs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] As a result, we’ve sometimes found that working from desired objectives backward to specific indicators works better than choosing indicators and then coming up with targets.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For maximum clarity, SLOs should specify how they’re measured and the conditions under which they’re valid.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] It’s both unrealistic and undesirable to insist that SLOs will be met 100% of the time: doing so can reduce the rate of innovation and deployment, require expensive, overly conservative solutions, or both.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Instead, it is better to allow an error budget—a rate at which the SLOs can be missed—and track that on a daily or weekly basis.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Upper management will probably want a monthly or quarterly assessment, too.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] The SLO violation rate can be compared against the error budget (see Motivation for Error Budgets), with the gap used as an input to the process that decides when to roll out new releases.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Choosing targets (SLOs) is not a purely technical activity because of the product and business implications, which should be reflected in both the SLIs and SLOs (and maybe SLAs) that are selected.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Similarly, it may be necessary to trade off certain product attributes against others within the constraints posed by staffing, time to market, hardware availability, and funding.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Complicated aggregations in SLIs can obscure changes to system performance, and are also harder to reason about.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] While it’s tempting to ask for a system that can scale its load "infinitely" without any latency increase and that is "always" available, this requirement is unrealistic.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Even a system that approaches such ideals will probably take a long time to design and build, and will be expensive to operate—and probably turn out to be unnecessarily better than what users would be happy (or even delighted) to have.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Choose just enough SLOs to provide good coverage of your system’s attributes.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Defend the SLOs you pick: if you can’t ever win a conversation about priorities by quoting a particular SLO, it’s probably not worth having that SLO.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] However, not all product attributes are amenable to SLOs: it’s hard to specify "user delight" with an SLO.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] You can always refine SLO definitions and targets over time as you learn about a system’s behavior.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] It’s better to start with a loose target that you tighten than to choose an overly strict target that has to be relaxed when you discover it’s unattainable.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] SLOs can—and should—be a major driver in prioritizing work for SREs and product developers, because they reflect what users care about.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] A good SLO is a helpful, legitimate forcing function for a development team.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] But a poorly thought-out SLO can result in wasted work if a team uses heroic efforts to meet an overly aggressive SLO, or a bad product if the SLO is too lax.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] SLOs are a massive lever: use them wisely.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Compare the SLIs to the SLOs, and decide whether or not action is needed.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] If action is needed, figure out *what* needs to happen in order to meet the target.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For example, if step 2 shows that request latency is increasing, and will miss the SLO in a few hours unless something is done, step 3 might include testing the hypothesis that the servers are CPU-bound, and deciding to add more of them to spread the load.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Without the SLO, you wouldn’t know whether (or when) to take action.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Publishing SLOs sets expectations for system behavior.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Users (and potential users) often want to know what they can expect from a service in order to understand whether it’s appropriate for their use case.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] For instance, a team wanting to build a photo-sharing website might want to avoid using a service that promises very strong durability and low cost in exchange for slightly lower availability, though the same service might be a perfect fit for an archival records management system.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Using a tighter internal SLO than the SLO advertised to users gives you room to respond to chronic problems before they become visible externally.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] An SLO buffer also makes it possible to accommodate reimplementations that trade performance for other attributes, such as cost or ease of maintenance, without having to disappoint users.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Users build on the reality of what you offer, rather than what you say you’ll supply, particularly for infrastructure services.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] If your service’s actual performance is much better than its stated SLO, users will come to rely on its current performance.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] throttling some requests, or designing the system so that it isn’t faster under light loads.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Understanding how well a system is meeting its expectations helps decide whether to invest in making the system faster, more available, and more resilient.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Alternatively, if the service is doing fine, perhaps staff time should be spent on other priorities, such as paying off technical debt, adding new features, or introducing other products.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Crafting an SLA requires business and legal teams to pick appropriate consequences and penalties for a breach.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] SRE’s role is to help them understand the likelihood and difficulty of meeting the SLOs contained in the SLA.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] Much of the advice on SLO construction is also applicable for SLAs.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] It is wise to be conservative in what you advertise to users, as the broader the constituency, the harder it is to change or delete SLAs that prove to be unwise or difficult to work with.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] 16Most people really mean SLO when they say "SLA." One giveaway: if somebody talks about an "SLA violation," they are almost always talking about a missed SLO.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] A real SLA violation might trigger a court case for breach of contract.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] 17If you can’t ever win a conversation about SLOs, it’s probably not worth having an SRE team for the product.
[src:service-level-objectives/service-level-objectives] 18Failure injection [Ben12] serves a different purpose, but can also help set expectations.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:service-level-objectives/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
